  <exercise label="Library__Hope__Multi2__12-01-Vector-fields__Vector-fields-01a">
    <webwork source="Library/Hope/Multi2/12-01-Vector-fields/Vector-fields-01a.pg" />
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p> Assume that <m>x,y \geq 0</m> for all of the vector fields in this question. Select an
        answer for each question and explain your reasoning. </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>\vF_1= y \vec{i}</m>. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>The vector field <m>\vF_1</m> is <ul>
                  <li>parallel to the x-axis</li>
                  <li>parallel to the y-axis</li>
                  <li>neither</li>
                </ul></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>As <m>x</m> increases, <ul>
                  <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                  <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                  <li>neither</li>
                </ul></p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>As <m>y</m> increases, <ul>
                  <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                  <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                  <li>neither</li>
                </ul></p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer> <p> The vector field <m>\vF_1</m> is parallel to the x-axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field does not change.  As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.</p> </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The vector field <m>\vF_1</m> is parallel to the x-axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field does not change.  As <m>y</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>\vF_2= \langle y, 1 \rangle</m>. 
          <ol>
          <li>
            <p>The vector field <m>\vF_2</m> is <ul>
                <li>parallel to the x-axis</li>
                <li>parallel to the y-axis</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>As <m>x</m> increases, <ul>
                <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>As <m>y</m> increases, <ul>
                <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer> <p> The vector field <m>\vF_2</m> is not parallel to either axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field does not change.  As <m>y</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.</p> </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The vector field <m>\vF_2</m> is not parallel to either axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field does not change.  As <m>y</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p>Let <m>\vF_3= (x+e^{1-y})\vec{j}</m>. 
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>The vector field <m>\vF_3</m> is <ul>
                <li>parallel to the x-axis</li>
                <li>parallel to the y-axis</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>As <m>x</m> increases, <ul>
                <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>As <m>y</m> increases, <ul>
                <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer> 
      <p>
        The vector field <m>\vF_3</m> is parallel to the <m>y</m>-axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.  As <m>y</m> increases, the length of the vector field decreases.
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The vector field <m>\vF_3</m> is parallel to the <m>y</m>-axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.  As <m>y</m> increases, the length of the vector field decreases.
      </p>
    </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>Let <m>\vF_4= \nabla(y^4+e^{2x})</m>. 
          <ol>
          <li>
            <p>The vector field <m>\vF_4</m> is <ul>
                <li>parallel to the x-axis</li>
                <li>parallel to the y-axis</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>As <m>x</m> increases, <ul>
                <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>As <m>y</m> increases, <ul>
                <li>the length of the vector field increases</li>
                <li>the length of the vector field decreases</li>
                <li>neither</li>
              </ul></p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      </statement>
      <answer> 
        <p>
          The vector field <m>\vF_4</m> is not parallel to either axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.  As <m>y</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The vector field <m>\vF_4</m> is not parallel to either axis. As <m>x</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases.  As <m>y</m> increases, the length of the vector field increases. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

